                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.01 Foreign Control/948: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hibbard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-05-17T15:00:00-00:44"
                            >May 17, 1935—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>14. Department’s telegram 5, May 14, 7 p.m. I see no reasons whatever to delay
                    recognition after the Liberian Congress repeals the Moratorium Act and ratifies
                    the Firestone agreements. Conditions are not perfect but they are slowly
                    improving and I feel very strongly that recognition will place us in a better
                    position to assist in the formation and operation of Barclay’s plan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hibbard</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
